      • getInputsToCompareToOutput

        public Iterable<String> getInputsToCompareToOutput()
        Description copied from interface: Buildable
        Get the set of input files whose contents should be hashed for the purpose of determining whether this rule is cached.

        Note that inputs are iterable and should generally be alphabetized so that lists with the same elements will be .equals() to one another. However, for some build rules (such as Genrule), the order of the inputs is significant and in these cases the inputs may be ordered in any way the rule feels most appropriate.

        Specified by:
        getInputsToCompareToOutput in interface Buildable

      • getAbiKey

        public Sha1HashCode getAbiKey()
        Description copied from interface: JavaLibraryRule
        Returns a SHA-1 hash that represents the ABI for the Java files returned by JavaLibraryRule.getJavaSrcs(). If JavaLibraryRule.getJavaSrcs() returns an empty collection, then this will return a non-absent value. The only requirement on the hash is that equal hashes imply equal ABIs.

        Because the ABI is computed as part of the build process, this rule cannot be invoked until after this rule is built.

        Specified by:
        getAbiKey in interface JavaLibraryRule

      • initializeFromDisk

        public void initializeFromDisk(OnDiskBuildInfo onDiskBuildInfo)
        Description copied from class: AbstractCachingBuildRule
        For a rule that is read from the build cache, it may have fields that would normally be populated by executing the steps returned by Buildable.getBuildSteps(BuildContext, BuildableContext). Because Buildable.getBuildSteps(BuildContext, BuildableContext) is not invoked for cached rules, a rule may need to implement this method to populate those fields in some other way. For a cached rule, this method will be invoked just before the future returned by AbstractCachingBuildRule.build(BuildContext) is resolved.
        Overrides:
        initializeFromDisk in class AbstractCachingBuildRule
        Parameters:
        onDiskBuildInfo - can be used to read metadata from disk to help initialize the rule.

        public String getPathToOutputFile()
        Description copied from interface: Buildable
        Currently, this is used by AbstractCachingBuildRule to determine which files should be be included in the BuildInfoRecorder. Ultimately, a Buildable should be responsible for updating the BuildInfoRecorder itself in its Buildable.getBuildSteps(BuildContext, BuildableContext) method. The use of this method should be restricted to things like buck targets --show_output.

      • appendToRuleKey

        public RuleKey.Builder appendToRuleKey(RuleKey.Builder builder)
                                throws IOException
        getRuleKey() and getRuleKeyWithoutDeps() uses this when constructing RuleKeys for this class. Every subclass that extends the rule state in a way that matters to idempotency must override appendToRuleKey(com.facebook.buck.rules.RuleKey.Builder) and append its state to the RuleKey.Builder returned by its superclass's appendToRuleKey(com.facebook.buck.rules.RuleKey.Builder) implementation. Example: 
         @Override
 protected RuleKey.Builder appendToRuleKey(RuleKey.Builder builder) {
   return super.appendToRuleKey(builder)
       .set("srcs", srcs),
       .set("resources", resources);
 }
        Overrides:
        appendToRuleKey in class AbstractCachingBuildRule
        Throws:
        IOException

      • getDeps

        public final ImmutableSortedSet<BuildRule> getDeps()
        Specified by:
        getDeps in interface BuildRule
        Returns:
        the set of rules that must be built before this rule. Normally, this matches the value of the deps argument for this build rule in the build file in which it was defined.

        However, there are special cases where other arguments pull in implicit dependencies (e.g., the keystore argument in android_binary). In these cases, the implicit dependencies are also included in the set returned by this method. The value of the original deps argument, as defined in the build file, must be accessed via a custom getter provided by the build rule.
